Big Data Basic Insights

Sudarshan

May 02, 2022

Motiviation

Over the past decade, researchers around the world have generated large amounts of information related to the human gut microbiome. Large scale population studies have cataloged the vast diversity in the human gut microbiome. I wanted to re-visit some of the basic features of the human gut microbiome that are often taken for granted. Such as how many species are present in an individuals gut/fecal sample? In literature, a variety of numbers are menthioned ranging from 100s to 1000s. Similarly, other questions which I am to visualize in this document. curatedMetagenomicData is a useful resource for getting basic insights from wealth of publicly available human metagenomes specifically from the gut.

Extract Data

We follow the simple steps outlined in the curatedMetagenomicData to select for samples marked as healthy in the database.
We extract relative abundance data.

# 2022-05-01
tse <- sampleMetadata |>
  filter(!is.na(age)) |>
  #filter(!is.na(alcohol)) |>
  filter(body_site == "stool") |>
  filter(disease == "healthy") |>
  select(where(~ !all(is.na(.x)))) |>
  returnSamples("relative_abundance", rownames = "short")
tse
saveRDS(tse, "data/curatedMgDTSE.rds")

Read stored data.

tse <- readRDS("data/curatedMgDTSE.rds")

tse.df <- tse.df |> 
  group_by(age_category) %>% 
  mutate(
    n = n(),
    median = median(observed.species),
    max = max(observed.species)
  ) %>% 
  ungroup()

tse.df <- tse.df |> 
  mutate(age_category = str_to_title(age_category))
table(tse.df$age_category)
## 
##     Adult     Child   Newborn Schoolage    Senior 
##      6042       801      2162       229       721
nsamples <- ncol(tse)

tse.df <- tse.df %>%
  mutate(age_category = fct_reorder(age_category, observed.species))

p.main <- ggplot(tse.df, aes(observed.species, age_category, color = age_category,
                             fill = age_category)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  stat_summary(
    geom = "linerange",
    fun.min = function(x) -Inf,
    fun.max = function(x) median(x, na.rm = TRUE),
    linetype = "dotted",
    orientation = "y",
    size = .7
  ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    alpha=0.2,
    width = .15, 
    outlier.shape = NA
  ) +
  ggdist::stat_halfeye(
    aes(
      y = age_category,
      color = age_category,
      fill = after_scale(colorspace::lighten(color, .5))
    ),
    shape = 18,
    point_size = 3,
    interval_size = 1.8,
    adjust = .5,
    .width = c(0, 1),
    show.legend = FALSE
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(x = median, label = format(round(median, 2), nsmall = 2)),
    stat = "unique",
    color = "white",
    fontface = "bold",
    size = 3.4,
    nudge_y = .15
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(x = max, label = glue::glue("n = {n}")),
    stat = "unique",
    fontface = "bold",
    size = 3.5,
    hjust = 0,
    nudge_x = .01,
    nudge_y = .02
  ) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(1.2, NA), clip = "off")+
  scale_color_manual("Age category",values = age.cols) +
  scale_fill_manual("Age category", values = age.cols) +
  labs(#title = "" ,
    subtitle = "How many 'species' are there in a gut microbiome?\nMedian values shown in plot",
    y="", x=glue::glue("Observed Species (N = {nsamples})"),
    caption = "Data: Pasolli E, Schiffer L, Manghi P, et. al., (2017).\nNature Methods, doi:10.1038/nmeth.4468.\nAccessed on 2022-05-01. Visualization by Shetty SA") +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major.x = element_line(size = .35),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 13, hjust = 1),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 13, hjust = 1),
    axis.ticks.length = unit(0, "lines"),
    plot.title.position = 'plot',
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, color = "grey30"),
    plot.margin = margin(10, 25, 10, 25),
    legend.position = "none",
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0, face = "italic", color="grey30")
  )

Which genera are dominant in different age groups?

dominant_taxa <- mia::countDominantTaxa(tse,
                                        rank = "genus",
                                        group = "age_category",
                                        abund_values = "relative_abundance", 
                                        na.rm = TRUE)

tax.plot <- dominant_taxa |> 
  group_by(dominant_taxa) |> 
  summarise(sum=sum(rel.freq)) |> 
  arrange(desc(sum)) |> 
  filter(sum >10) |> 
  pull(dominant_taxa)

dominant_taxa |> 
  mutate(dominant_taxa2 = ifelse(dominant_taxa %in% tax.plot, dominant_taxa, "Other")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(age_category, rel.freq)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill=dominant_taxa2))

p.dom <- dominant_taxa |> 
  mutate(dominant_taxa2 = ifelse(dominant_taxa %in% tax.plot, dominant_taxa, "Other")) |>

  mutate(age_category = str_to_title(age_category),
